<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fiorentino &amp; Tocora &amp; Ramirez" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Metopiellus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Metopiellus guanano" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guanano">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Metopiellus guanano</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is most similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. painensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="painensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. painensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4269.1.5" author="Asenjo, A" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="115 - 123" refId="B1" refString="Asenjo, A, Ferreira, RL, Zampaulo, RDA, 2017. Description of Metopiellus painensis sp. nov. (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae), first troglobitic Pselaphinae from Brazil. Zootaxa 4269 (1): 115 - 123, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4269.1.5" title="Description of Metopiellus painensis sp. nov. (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae), first troglobitic Pselaphinae from Brazil." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4269.1.5" volume="4269" year="2017">Asenjo et. al., 2017</bibRefCitation>
. Yet, it can be distinguished by the presence of a significant number of autapomorphic character states, such as: the presence of a prominent, horn-like spine on the vertexal region of the head (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. ♂ Metopiellus guanano sp. nov., holotype A habitus, left lateral view B habitus, dorsal view C left antenna, lateral view D habitus, ventral view E head and pronotum, dorsal view F head and pronotum, left lateral view. Scale bars: 1 mm (A, B, D); 0.5 mm (C, E, F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.76077.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705118" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1A,F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Detail of Metopiellus guanano sp. nov., head and pronotal spines, traced in white A male head and pronotum, left lateral view B female head and pronotum, left lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.76077.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705121" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4A,B</figureCitation>
), the presence of 4 distinct pronotal spines and 2 deep elytral sulci, as well as the shape of the aedeagus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. ♂ Metopiellus guanano sp. nov., holotype A segment VIII (tergum VIII and sternum VIII), lateral view B sternum VIII C tergum VIII D, aedeagus, ventral view E aedeagus, dorsal view F aedeagus, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (A); 0.2 mm (B, C); 0.2 mm (D-F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.76077.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705119" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2D-F</figureCitation>
) and thick pilosity covering the entire body (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. ♂ Metopiellus guanano sp. nov., holotype A habitus, left lateral view B habitus, dorsal view C left antenna, lateral view D habitus, ventral view E head and pronotum, dorsal view F head and pronotum, left lateral view. Scale bars: 1 mm (A, B, D); 0.5 mm (C, E, F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.76077.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705118" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
