<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Habitat and ecological notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The specimens were collected through Winkler sampling in primary forest in the northern Colombian Amazon. The sampled localities correspond to areas with a relative humidity of 84% and an average temperature of 28 °C; at both locations the vegetation was characteristic of a humid tropical forest. The processes that determine the diversity and floristic composition of the forests are not well known (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.14483/udistrital.jour.colomb.for.2009.1.a06" author="Cano, A" journalOrPublisher="Colombia Forestal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="63 - 80" refId="B4" refString="Cano, A, Stevenson, PR, 2008. Diversidad y composicion floristica de tres tipos de bosque en la estacion biologica Caparu, Vaupes. Colombia Forestal 12: 63 - 80, DOI: https://doi.org/10.14483/udistrital.jour.colomb.for.2009.1.a06" title="Diversidad y composicion floristica de tres tipos de bosque en la estacion biologica Caparu, Vaupes." url="https://doi.org/10.14483/udistrital.jour.colomb.for.2009.1.a06" volume="12" year="2008">Cano and Stevenson 2008</bibRefCitation>
). The sampling in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Cucúra">Cucura</normalizedToken>
was carried out at no more than 20 m from a body of water; the area had been slightly disturbed by the elimination of plants from the understory and the terrain was humid due to recent rains.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Sampling at Villa 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Fátima">Fatima</normalizedToken>
was carried out in a submontane primary forest. The collection area was mostly pristine, with predominantly arboreal vegetation with little understory vegetation. This may be due to the superficial first granite layer of the hill (Tepui) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-59773-2_15" author="Groeger, A" editor="Porembski, S" journalOrPublisher="Ecological Studies. Springer Berlin Heidelberg, Berlin, Heidelberg" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="291 - 314" refId="B7" refString="Groeger, A, 2000. Flora and Vegetation of Inselbergs of Venezuelan Guayana. In: Porembski, S, Barthlott, W, Eds., Inselbergs. Ecological Studies. Springer Berlin Heidelberg, Berlin, Heidelberg: 291 - 314, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-59773-2_15" title="Flora and Vegetation of Inselbergs of Venezuelan Guayana." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-59773-2_15" volumeTitle="Inselbergs." year="2000">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gröger">Groeger</normalizedToken>
2000
</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1865" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Apterostigma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apterostigma pilosum" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Apterostigma pilosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ant complex (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11606/issn.2176-7793.v34i5p121-221" author="Lattke, JE" journalOrPublisher="Arquivos de Zoologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="121 - 221" refId="B8" refString="Lattke, JE, 1997. Revision del genero Apterostigma mayr: (hymenoptera: formicidae). Arquivos de Zoologia 34 (5): 121 - 221, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11606/issn.2176-7793.v34i5p121-221" title="Revision del genero Apterostigma mayr: (hymenoptera: formicidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11606/issn.2176-7793.v34i5p121-221" volume="34" year="1997">Lattke 1997</bibRefCitation>
) were abundant in the same samples as the holotype and paratype of the new species. It is important to highlight this morphological similarity to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1865" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Apterostigma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apterostigma" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Apterostigma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, but further studies are required to indicate any type of relationship between the new beetle and these ants.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The new species is named after the indigenous communities located at the type locality. The Guanano people inhabit the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Vaupés">Vaupes</normalizedToken>
River region of Colombia, from the Santa Cruz area below 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mitú">Mitu</normalizedToken>
to Ibacaba in the lower 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Vaupés">Vaupes</normalizedToken>
, near the border with Brazil (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1086/521730" author="Stenzel, K" journalOrPublisher="International Journal of American Linguistics" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="331 - 366" refId="B14" refString="Stenzel, K, 2007. Glottalization and Other Suprasegmental Features in Wanano. International Journal of American Linguistics 73 (3): 331 - 366, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1086/521730" title="Glottalization and Other Suprasegmental Features in Wanano." url="https://doi.org/10.1086/521730" volume="73" year="2007">Stenzel 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
